ike the World Bank. He concludes that if there is to be a solution to the dilemmas of the Nile Basin countries, it must be based upon contractual understandings, brokered by third-party funders, and based on the national interests of each basin state.“This excellent book makes a significant contribution to the rational discussion of Nile conflicts and should be helpful to many of the other 282 international river basins facing similar problems.”-Peter P. Rogers, Harvard University  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aWater resources developmentxGovernment policyzNile River Watershed. 0aWater resources developmentzNile River WatershedxInternational cooperation. 0aWater-supplyzNile River WatershedxManagementxInternational cooperation. 7aNATURE / Natural Resources.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030012768340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300127683423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300127683/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles